I'm not about to sign up for multiple internet services without being able to afford the upfront fees, so I usually stick with just one provider.
It's really frustrating when I try to stream videos or upload large files for work, but my internet just won't buff, because of these ridiculously small monthly limits on my plan.
It's frustrating when you're trying to stream your favorite show but it keeps buffering because they just don't seem to have the infrastructure up here.
It's frustrating to not know how to set up my own Wi-Fi when our internet supplier just teaches people with older internet plans what to do.
It's hard for me to afford a decent internet plan with what I'm making right now, so it feels like sacrifice just to get online.
I wish there was better internet here - literally nowhere can get a decent connection within miles of my house.
It's really frustrating when I'm trying to stay connected with family and friends while we're out and about.
It's hard to stream my favorite shows on Netflix when I'm stuck with such a small monthly limit for data.
Internet speeds are way too slow to watch my favorite shows with anyone who's not in the same city as me.
I try to get everything done at work that I do at home when they don't offer more bandwidth because that's my only affordable option sometimes.
It's really frustrating when there are always compatibility issues with new apps and websites that don't work properly on my old phone.
It's really frustrating when I try to stream a movie because my signal keeps dropping out due to too much traffic on the limited plan.
It's frustrating when I try to use new software tools but can't figure out how to get started.
I've tried to cancel multiple times just to get an answer to why I was overcharged for that one month.
It's just really inconvenient when family members want to watch TV shows on Netflix at 9pm.
I stick to my local library because it's free and has most of what I need, rather than relying on something that's not really adding value to my life.
I usually forget my favorite websites when shopping for internet plans in general.
I avoid buying new devices because our phone and tablet are always running out of data and it's too limiting for school and family use.
It's really frustrating when you're trying to stream something but the playback keeps buffering and dropping.
I prefer to watch TV on my living room screen instead of using my phone's slow data because I can see everything clearly that way.
I don't use the internet as much as I want to since their monthly plans are way out of my budget.
I really struggle to get set up with new tech websites or streaming services because of how much it costs each time I want to use them.
I'm really frustrated with having to cut back on streaming and downloading due to how expensive internet plans just aren't affordable for me anymore.
I'm put off by how expensive those extra fees are – it's always frustrating to sign up for a new internet plan just to pay another charge that doesn't seem fair.
It's really inconvenient when my roommate needs me to help with their work and all they can do is sit at home on Wi-Fi.
I almost never ask for help with anything online because nothing ever seems to address my specific problem.
Data overages really slow down my whole browsing experience and make it hard to watch videos.
I'd be honest with myself if I registered everything on one site – it's just not worth the money upfront for the occasional few minutes of extra convenience.
I really don't have a smartwatch because the one-time setup fee was way too steep for me.
It's really expensive to get reliable internet at home, so we mostly stick to public Wi-Fi when we're out and about these days.
It's really frustrating when you wait for what feels like forever for just one video clip to buffer.
I'm really afraid to click on any suspicious links because I've lost money to phishing scams in the past.
